<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="feedback-management">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-operations</domain>
    <summary>Systematic pipeline for collecting feedback from multiple channels, categorizing it against a locked taxonomy, aggregating patterns, linking to backlog items, and closing the loop when features ship.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>feedback</tag>
      <tag>customer-research</tag>
      <tag>triage</tag>
      <tag>product-signals</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Feedback Management</title>

    <summary>Systematic pipeline for collecting feedback from multiple channels, categorizing it against a locked taxonomy, aggregating patterns by topic and segment, linking top clusters to backlog items, and closing the loop with users when their requests ship. The pipeline runs: Collect → Categorize → Analyze → Prioritize → Act → Close Loop. Taxonomy is code-versioned; changes require a migration and re-tag run.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Feedback scattered across support tickets, in-app forms, app store reviews, sales calls, and social creates a situation where loudest voices dominate decisions and quiet churners go unheard. Without a structured system, important signals drown in noise, users feel unheard, and teams build for vocal minorities. Centralizing, weighting by segment/ARR (not raw mention count), and closing the loop converts feedback from a complaint queue into a product intelligence channel.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Feedback arriving from 3+ channels and a human can no longer triage in real time.</item>
        <item>You want a daily/weekly digest of categorized, deduplicated, prioritized requests linked to backlog items.</item>
        <item>Automated close-the-loop emails needed when a requested feature ships.</item>
        <item>Sentiment tracking against a release or pricing change is required.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fewer than 20 feedback items per week — manual handling beats pipeline overhead.</item>
        <item>High-stakes B2B accounts where every quote requires named-customer context — keep human in the loop end-to-end.</item>
        <item>Regulated industries (medical, finance) where verbatim handling has compliance constraints — PII redaction first.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="feedback-sources">
      <list>
        <item>Support tickets — high volume, high quality (real issues, concrete pain)</item>
        <item>In-app feedback widget — medium volume, medium quality (prompted, context-aware)</item>
        <item>App store reviews — medium volume, mixed quality (public, harder to follow up)</item>
        <item>Sales calls — low volume, high quality (prospect pain, concrete context)</item>
        <item>NPS surveys — medium volume, medium quality (prompted, sentiment-reliable)</item>
        <item>User interviews — low volume, very high quality (deep intent, behavioral)</item>
        <item>Social media — variable volume and quality (unsolicited, harder to categorize)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="categorization-taxonomy">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Lock the taxonomy in a versioned file. Treat taxonomy changes as schema migrations: write a migration script and re-tag existing items before applying.</statement>
        <rationale>Taxonomy drift produces categorization inconsistency over time, making trend analysis unreliable. Versioning makes changes auditable and reversible.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Type: bug (something broken), request (new capability), enhancement (improve existing), confusion (UX/navigation issue), praise, complaint</item>
        <item>Topic: create a product-specific taxonomy — typical: onboarding, core-feature-A, billing, integrations, performance, mobile, other</item>
      </list>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent over-categorizing ambiguous items as "enhancement" (catch-all).</description>
        <reason>Enhancement becomes a black hole for uncategorized items. Force "bug" when verbatim contains "broken", "can't", "fails". Force specific topic or reject with request for taxonomy update.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="processing-pipeline">
      <list>
        <item>Step 1: Centralize — single source of truth (Canny, Productboard, Notion, or spreadsheet); auto-import from support + in-app</item>
        <item>Step 2: Triage — type, topic, source, segment, sentiment per item; always preserve verbatim</item>
        <item>Step 3: Aggregate — volume by category, trends over time, top requests by mention count</item>
        <item>Step 4: Prioritize — connect to backlog items; weight by segment/ARR, not raw count</item>
        <item>Step 5: Act — build (add to roadmap), won't do (document reason), need more info, already planned</item>
        <item>Step 6: Close loop — email "you asked, we built" when feature ships; respond within 30 days of ship date</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Weight feedback by ARR or segment, not raw mention count. One enterprise complaint can outweigh 50 free-tier votes.</statement>
        <rationale>Volume bias: vocal free users post many tickets; at-risk enterprise accounts may post zero. Raw count ranking optimizes for the wrong population.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always store the verbatim alongside structured fields. Never lose the original quote.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent rewrites lose intent signals. Original wording reveals tone, context, and use case that structured fields cannot capture.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-workflow">
      <list>
        <item>triage agent (per item): outputs structured JSON — type, topic, sentiment, segment, severity, dedup_hash, suggested_backlog_link</item>
        <item>weekly aggregator (per week): groups by topic + dedup_id, surfaces top requests with mention counts and segment breakdown</item>
        <item>close-loop agent (on deploy): watches deploy pipeline, drafts "you asked, we built" emails for human approval before send</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Auto-responding without human review is a brand risk. Default mode = draft and queue; human approves before send.</statement>
        <rationale>Wrong close-loop email (wrong feature attributed to wrong user, incorrect status) destroys trust harder than no email at all.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Agent triage prompt pattern">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Triage one feedback item. Output JSON only:
{
  "type": "bug|request|enhancement|confusion|praise|complaint",
  "topic": "<one of [taxonomy ids]>",
  "sentiment": "positive|neutral|negative",
  "segment": "<plan or persona>",
  "severity": 1-5,
  "dedup_hash": "<sha1 of normalized verbatim>",
  "suggested_backlog_link": "<existing issue id or null>",
  "rationale": "<<= 240 chars>"
}
Reject if you would invent a topic outside the supplied taxonomy.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="monthly-review-example">
      <example type="good" title="Monthly Feedback Review with Actionable Output">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Total feedback this month: 150 items
Top category: Integrations (40%)
Top request: Slack integration (25 mentions across 18 unique users)
Emerging pattern: Mobile app requests up 3x vs last month

Actions:
- Slack integration: added to Q2 roadmap; emailed 25 requesters
- Mobile: insufficient data for roadmap; scheduled 6 user interviews
- Billing complaints: 3 bugs fixed in current sprint

Close-loop sent: 25 emails for Slack roadmap addition
Feedback→roadmap conversion rate this month: 8% (target >5%)]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="app-store-response-strategy">
      <list>
        <item>1-2 star reviews: respond within 24h, apologize, offer direct support channel, log in feedback system</item>
        <item>3-4 star reviews: thank and ask what would make it 5 stars, log the gap</item>
        <item>5 star reviews: thank and ask for referrals or testimonial</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a quarterly drift audit: sample 50 LLM-categorized items, have a human re-tag, measure agreement rate. If below 80%, retrain or update the prompt.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM categorization drifts as product evolves and language patterns change. Without periodic audit, the taxonomy gradually loses meaning.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="deduplication">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use embedding similarity (cosine &gt;= 0.85) for deduplication, not full-text match. Paraphrases of the same issue are the same issue.</statement>
        <rationale>Naive full-text dedup misses paraphrases. Counting "search is slow" and "search takes forever" as two separate requests undercounts the true signal by half.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending raw feedback verbatim with emails or account IDs to LLM provider.</description>
        <reason>PII in LLM calls may violate GDPR DPA. Strip emails, phone numbers, account IDs with a regex pre-pass or dedicated scrubber agent before any LLM call.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using raw vote counts from Canny or Productboard as prioritization input.</description>
        <reason>Vote count correlates poorly with retention impact. One churned enterprise customer who never voted matters more than 50 free users who all voted.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Promoting a feedback cluster to roadmap item without human review of the decision.</description>
        <reason>Feedback volume may reflect vocal minority, not majority pain. Human checkpoint before roadmap promotion prevents shipping for the wrong users.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="human-in-loop-checkpoints">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Three mandatory human checkpoints: (1) before any outbound message, (2) before promoting feedback cluster to roadmap item, (3) before changing taxonomy.</statement>
        <rationale>Each of these has irreversible effects: sent email cannot be unsent, roadmap items create expectations, taxonomy changes invalidate historical analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Lock the taxonomy in a versioned file; require a migration script + re-tag run when it changes.</item>
        <item>Always store the verbatim alongside structured fields — never lose the original quote.</item>
        <item>Weight feedback by ARR / segment, not raw mention count. One enterprise complaint can outweigh 50 free-tier votes.</item>
        <item>Run a quarterly "drift audit" — sample 50 LLM-categorized items, have a human re-tag, measure agreement.</item>
        <item>Close the loop within 30 days of ship — agents can draft, humans approve, system sends.</item>
        <item>Track "feedback → roadmap" conversion rate as an internal KPI; if &lt; 5%, the funnel is decorative.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/feedback-log.md" purpose="Raw feedback table with category breakdown by month, top requests with segment and status."/>
      <template path="templates/feedback-responses.md" purpose="Three response templates: feature shipped, not planned, needs more info."/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/triage.py" purpose="Single-item triage: normalizes text, computes dedup hash, calls LLM with strict JSON schema, validates topic against taxonomy."/>
    </scripts>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.productboard.com/glossary/customer-feedback/"/>
      <link href="https://www.intercom.com/blog/"/>
      <link href="https://www.lennysnewsletter.com/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
